sec.p:
We start with the marginal component. For k and m such that Skm=1, let θkm=(θkm1,θkm2,θkm3), be the genotype frequencies of each biallelic marker—a marker that has only 3 states (AA, Aa, aa) based on the number of minor alleles it has—in the marginal component of population k. Then, due to independent effects of markers in this group, we can write the likelihood of the marginal component of the subpopulation k as follows:
(1)P(G1k|θk,C,Sk)=∏m:Skm=1{∏j=13θkmjnkmjmar}
where nkmjmar is the number of individuals in subpopulation k that has jth genotype for marker m.

The last genotype component to model is the null component. The parameters of the null component are shared across all components, i.e. a marker that is not related to the phenotype should have the same allelic distribution as other subpopulations in which it is assigned to the null component. Let ψm=(ψm1,ψm2,ψm3) be the genotype frequencies of a marker m in the general population. Then, we have:
(3)P(G0k|ψ,C,Sk)=∏m:Skm=0{∏j=13ψmjnmjnull}
where nmjnull is the number of the occurrence of state j for marker m across all individuals where it is classified as a null marker.
